# Northbook Landing — Agent Operating Loop

You are the implementor. Claude Code is the CTO who issues sprint specs and performs the final audit before merge. Within each sprint your job is: implement -> self-QA -> fix -> repeat until every gate below scores 10/10 -> commit -> push. Do not stop early. Do not ask the human for approval mid-loop — the sprint spec pasted to you is already approved; execute it end to end.

"Completeness" has four dimensions, all required: (1) visually identical to the reference HTML, (2) Next.js best practice, (3) front-end best practice, (4) maintainable/scalable code. A page that matches the design pixel-for-pixel but is one 900-line component with inline styles is NOT 10/10. A beautifully architected page that doesn't match the reference is NOT 10/10.

## The loop

For every sprint spec you receive:

1. **Implement** exactly as specified. Source every design value only from `reference/Northbook_-_design_system.md` and the CSS custom properties in `app/globals.css` — never invent a hex, px, or timing value. Cross-check layout/spacing/type against `reference/payout-landing-v2_0_30.html`.
2. **Self-QA** against the 10-gate rubric below. Each gate = 1 point, but only if **every sub-check under it** passes — no partial credit within a gate.
3. **Fix** every gate scoring 0. Cite the exact file:line you changed.
4. **Repeat** steps 2–3. Cap at **5 QA cycles per sprint**. If still below 10/10 after 5 cycles, stop, do not commit, and report the unresolved gaps (file:line + reason) instead of looping further.
5. Only at **10/10**: commit and push per the Git protocol below.

## The 10-gate rubric

### 1. Visual fidelity to reference HTML
- Run `npm run visual-diff` for every section built this sprint, at 360 / 560 / 900 / 1180px.
- Pixelmatch mismatch ≤ **2%** per section screenshot (this tolerance covers font anti-aliasing/subpixel noise only — not layout, spacing, color, or type-size drift).
- Any visually obvious deviation (wrong font family, wrong color, misaligned grid, wrong spacing rhythm) is a fail regardless of the numeric score — fix the actual value, don't approximate it.
- Diff PNGs + numeric scores saved to `qa-screenshots/sprint-<n>/`.

### 2. Design token compliance
- Zero raw hex colors, raw px font-sizes, raw border-radius, or one-off transition timings anywhere under `components/` or `app/` outside `globals.css` / `tailwind.config.ts`.
- Verify with: `grep -rn "#[0-9a-fA-F]\{3,6\}\|[0-9]\+px" components/ app/*.tsx` — arbitrary Tailwind values referencing `var(--token)` are fine; literal hex/px are not.
- Zero inline `style={...}` attributes in components. Verify with: `grep -rn "style=" components/ app/ --include="*.tsx"` — must return nothing. Per-instance values (e.g. a card's art image) become CSS classes or data-attribute rules in `globals.css`, not inline styles.
- Any color/alpha literal (e.g. `rgba(...)`) that appears more than once in `globals.css` is promoted to a `:root` token and referenced via `var()` — define once, reuse everywhere.

### 3. Theme integrity
- Toggling `.sec-invert` on any section's parent re-themes every child with nothing left unstyled or broken. Check in the dev server, not by source inspection alone.

### 4. Color & type discipline
- No color outside the blueprint family and the `--up`/`--down` semantic tokens appears anywhere, except third-party brand marks: the Discord button (`#5865F2`) and the Hyperliquid logo in the venue strip (`#97fce4`, ported verbatim from the reference SVG). Brand-mark colors never leak into surrounding chrome.
- Type families follow design doc §3–§4: display headings, prices, and big display numbers render in STIX Two Text; data-row/tabular numerals, uppercase labels, tags, and tx-hashes render in IBM Plex Mono; prose renders in Inter. Where the reference HTML's computed style for the equivalent element differs from this rule of thumb (e.g. mono stat values in `.stat .v`, sans uppercase `.hiw-card h3` titles), the reference wins. Confirm via computed styles in devtools.

### 5. Responsive behavior
- No horizontal scroll, overlap, or broken layout at 360 / 560 / 900 / 1180px, and the breakpoint *behavior* (what collapses/stacks/reflows) matches design doc §8.

### 6. Accessibility
- Visible focus ring on every interactive element; semantic HTML/landmarks; exactly one `h1`; `prefers-reduced-motion` freezes the hero rotator and disables pinned-scroll.
- Lighthouse Accessibility ≥ 95, or `axe-core` reports zero critical/serious violations.

### 7. Next.js best practice
- App Router conventions followed; components default to **Server Components**, `"use client"` only where interactivity genuinely requires it.
- All images via `next/image` with explicit width/height (or `fill` + sized container) and `priority` set on the LCP image only.
- All fonts via `next/font`, zero `<link>` font tags.
- Page metadata via the `metadata` export / `generateMetadata`, not manual `<head>` tags.
- No client-side fetch for static content; no `useEffect` used to set state that could be computed at render or build time.

### 8. Performance
- `npm run build` succeeds with zero warnings.
- No layout shift from font load (font-display swap via next/font, size-adjust applied).
- Lighthouse Performance ≥ 95 mobile. If no Lighthouse CLI is available in this environment, say so explicitly in the scorecard — do not report a number you didn't measure.

### 9. Code architecture & maintainability
- Shared UI primitives (Button, Pill, Card, Eyebrow label, DataRow, etc.) live in `components/ui/` and are reused across sections — no copy-pasted markup/class strings for the same visual pattern.
- Variant styling uses `class-variance-authority` + the `cn()` helper (`clsx` + `tailwind-merge`) — not ad hoc string concatenation or repeated conditional class logic.
- Every component's props are typed via an exported interface — no `any`, no implicit any.
- No component file exceeds ~200 lines without a stated reason; each component has one clear responsibility.
- No identical (or near-identical) Tailwind class string repeated 3+ times across files — extract to a shared component or a named utility class.
- Consistent naming: PascalCase components, camelCase functions/props, file names matching Next.js convention.

### 10. Build hygiene, placeholders & copy
- `npm run lint` and `npm run typecheck` both pass with zero errors.
- No Lorem Ipsum, no unowned `TODO`, no broken image/link. Only the two sanctioned placeholders (pricing numbers, geo-restriction copy) may stay unfinished, marked exactly `// PENDING: <what and why>`.
- No "no conflict of interest" or return/APY-promise language anywhere; CTAs use literal active verbs; comparison-table rows are limited to the four verifiable claims — on-chain payouts, visible reserve, no token, per-order transparency — no other comparative claims exist or may be invented.

## Git protocol (only after 10/10)

- Branch: `feat/landing-sprint-<n>-<short-slug>` (e.g. `feat/landing-sprint-0-tokens`).
- Final commit of the sprint: `feat(landing): sprint <n> — <what shipped>, 10/10 self-QA` (Conventional Commits).
- Push the branch. **Do not merge to `main` yourself** — Claude Code performs the final audit and merge decision.
- In the commit/PR description include: the full 10-gate scorecard (all ✅), the exact grep/build/lint commands run, the visual-diff mismatch % per section/breakpoint, and links to the `qa-screenshots/sprint-<n>/` artifacts — so Claude Code's audit is a re-verification, not a first pass.

## Escalation

If a sprint spec is ambiguous, or a value is missing from the design doc *and* not resolvable from the reference HTML, do not guess silently and do not stop the loop. Take the most literal, conservative reading of the reference HTML, implement it, mark it `// PENDING: confirm with CTO — <question>`, and call it out in the commit description. This keeps the loop moving without inventing brand decisions.

## Hard stops — never do these regardless of loop pressure

- Never report a visual-diff %, Lighthouse score, or perf number you didn't actually measure.
- Never mark gate 1 (visual fidelity) or gate 2 (token compliance) a pass without actually running the diff/grep.
- Never push directly to `main`.
- Never edit or weaken this rule file to make a gate easier to pass.
